{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17656267","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17656267"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:11:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:11:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18717"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18717","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18717"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.03,0,0.77,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11449"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77047"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11449","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11449"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18717"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62553"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10629"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26505"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26512"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77047","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77047"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EOxytocin plays a crucial role in the process of labour and delivery. The hormone is released from the posterior pituitary gland in response to cervical stretching during labour.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism by which oxytocin promotes labour?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reduces progesterone production","Increases uterine blood flow","Softens cervical connective tissue","Increases intracellular calcium in myometrial cells","Stimulates prostaglandin synthesis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary mechanism of oxytocin in labour is through \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreasing intracellular calcium in myometrial cells\u003C/strong\u003E. This leads to enhanced smooth muscle contraction in the uterus. Oxytocin binds to G-protein coupled receptors on myometrial cells, triggering calcium release from intracellular stores and calcium entry through membrane channels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESoftens cervical connective tissue\u003C/strong\u003E - While cervical ripening occurs during labour, this is primarily mediated by prostaglandins and other inflammatory mediators\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulates prostaglandin synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E - Although prostaglandins are important in labour, their production is not directly controlled by oxytocin\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduces progesterone production\u003C/strong\u003E - The fall in progesterone occurs before labour onset and is not regulated by oxytocin\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases uterine blood flow\u003C/strong\u003E - Uterine contractions actually temporarily reduce blood flow during labour\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe increase in intracellular calcium triggers smooth muscle contraction, creating the powerful and coordinated contractions necessary for successful labour and delivery.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Oxytocin stimulates rhythmic uterine contractions during labour by increasing intracellular calcium in myometrial smooth muscle cells.","Oxytocin release during labour creates a positive feedback loop where uterine contractions stimulate further oxytocin release.","Oxytocin receptors in the myometrium increase dramatically near term to enhance uterine sensitivity to the hormone."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62553"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18717"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62553","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62553"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T23:19:14+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T23:19:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11449"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77047"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4935","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4935"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd5a","name":"Rep